{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512828"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:01:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:01:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11967"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11967"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.44,0.09,0.24,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4559"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111856"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4559"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11967"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93927"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"9143"},{"type":"tags","id":"9144"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6825"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6844"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13761"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45450"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111856"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 41-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner as he has developed pain around his anus. He explains that the pain is present all of the time and is so bad that it is making it difficult for him to pass bowel motions. The symptoms began two days ago and have become progressively more severe. He can now feel a tender swelling several centimetres in front of his anus. He has not had any passage of fresh blood or noticed blood on the toilet paper after a bowel motion. His bowel motions are regular and he has not noticed any change in the appearance. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes and asthma. He thinks he had a similar problem about eight years ago but that settled on its own accord.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 124/82 mmHg, pulse 96/min and temperature 37.8\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. On inspection of his perineum a reddened and swollen area is visible immediately anterior to the anal verge.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anal fissure","Anorectal abscess","Prolapsed internal haemorrhoid","Thrombosed external haemorrhoid","Pilonidal abscess"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is most likely a perianal or \u003Cstrong\u003Eanorectal abscess.\u003C/strong\u003E This condition typically manifests with symptoms of severe anorectal pain, systemic signs of infection (tachycardia, fever) and a feeling of swelling in the affected region. Risk factors for the condition include Crohn\u0027s disease, presence of an anal fissure, male sex, age 21-40 and diabetes (higher infection risk). This condition does not typically present with bowel changes or the passage of blood / blood on the toilet paper after a bowel motion. Similarly, it does not commonly present with pain on defecation. The commonest - and usual - cause for perianal abscess formation is perianal crypt infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnal fissure\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely to be the diagnosis in this case due to the lack of blood present in any form and the constant nature of the pain. Symptoms of an anal fissure are usually described as intermittent, easing somewhat between passages of stools and exaggerated during a bowel motion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ethrombosed external haemorrhoid\u003C/strong\u003E will present with sudden onset severe rectal pain and swelling. Due to their presence distal to the dentate line, external haemorrhoids present with more specific and pinpoint pain as they are covered by nociceptive skin. They may also be described as presenting with pruritus in the anal region. They do have a tendency to bleed and are less likely to be the answer in this case. A \u003Cstrong\u003Eprolapsed internal haemorrhoid\u003C/strong\u003E will present with a feeling of fullness or a lump around the anus and blood being present on the toilet paper after a bowel motion. Due to the haemorrhoid being internal and proximal to the dentate line, these are usually less painful, with more dull /achy pain (visceral pain) than an external thrombosed haemorrhoid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epilonidal abscess\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by embedding of a collection of hairs into the skin of the natal cleft in the sacrococcygeal area, or in the cleft of the buttocks. They present with pain, swelling and occasionally discharge in the region posterior to the anus, hence does not fit the anatomical description of the above case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anorectal abscesses may be debilitating condition of presenting with anorectal pain and swelling with systemic features of infection"],"references":["Marcus RH, Stine RJ, Cohen MA. Perirectal abscess. Ann Emerg Med. 1995 May;25(5):597-603. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/7741334/","Foxx-Orenstein AE, Umar SB, Crowell MD. Common anorectal disorders. Gastroenterol Hepatol (N Y). 2014 May;10(5):294-301. PMID: 24987313; PMCID: PMC4076876. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24987313/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93927"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11967"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93927"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-20T14:42:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-20T14:42:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4559"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111856"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","